CHAT.comment: Peter talked a great deal at this sample , producing about 600 different comprehensible utterances. he also imitated a great deal , by far the majority of the imitations being immediate and unique. he had also acquired some formulas which he used very often. among the the most frequent were "look at that" , "uhhuh" , "what's that" (and "what's that there"). he also used "no" far more than he ever had before. it occurred over 30 times as a single word and it occurred in combinations with other words. it expressed non-existence (no monkey). it contrasted with uhhuh as an answer to a question (does it stick? no). when Mother answered the phone and Peter wanted to he said , "no me!". no complete analysis of Peter's use of negation has been done. (as of 6-5-72). Peter's family had made a trip to California between the last sample and this one. he was able to answer a few questions about it but seemed not to have any real understanding of those questions except as routines. both Peter and Jennifer had bad colds and Peter's cold made it hard to understand him sometimes. new: bendable people; the single most frequent word--in all combinations-- was "there". Peter06 has been checked for missing intonation.
